            <p>Philadelphia<lb/></p>
            <p>At the request of Mr N. Polano&#8212;a<lb/> teacher <del>well</del> thoroughly qualified to impart Hebrew learn&#45;<lb/>ing&#8212;I examined Wm Buzonowsky&#91;&#63;&#93; in several bran<lb/>ches.<lb/></p>
            <p>Considering that a year ago the lad knew scarce<lb/>ly the first rudiments of the language of Holy<lb/> Writ&#44; and that he was altogether unacquainted<lb/> with that of the Rabbis&#44; I feel no hesitation in<lb/> <del>stating</del> saying that he has done remarkably well.<lb/></p>
            <p>We can translate <del>promiscuously</del> with <del>tolerable influence</del> a degree of fluency<lb/> historical books of the Bible&#8212;except those portions which<lb/> are written in Aramaic&#8212;and he can understandingly<lb/> give many of the grammatical rules.  He<lb/> possesses some knowledge of the <del>Jewish</del> Hebrew covenants&#44; and the little<lb/> <del>of the Mishnah taught him so far</del> which has been taught him in the Mishnah&#44; he has retained.<lb/>  <del>The</del> From the questions I put to him in the history of our<lb/> people&#44; I judge that he is tolerably familiar with it&#44; as far<lb/> as the wars <del>of independence</del> under the Maccabees.<lb/>  And I am glad to be abel to add from reliable in&#45;<lb/>formation&#44; that young Buzonowsky&#91;&#63;&#93; is very studious&#44;<lb/> and of a pious disposition.<lb/></p>
            <p>Elul 2d 5642&#8212;August 17<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1882.  S. Morais<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
